  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1277657257" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1277657257" />
    <a title="Joe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30725889-joe"><img alt="Joe" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1277657257?book_show_action=true">May 11, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe" href="/user/show/30725889-joe">Joe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780330468626" href="/book/show/6474158-the-informers">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30725889-joe?shelf=transgressive">transgressive</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1277657257" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6648538585634791183">Ellis is a one-trick pony. This short story collection is simply a regurgitation of <i>Less than Zero</i>. A horrendous effort from an author who proves to be more overrated with each book that I read by him. <i>The Informers</i> contains stories where absolutely nothing happens and the characters are all the same. Ellis confuses apathy; he thinks by writing as such it will deliver this sense. It&apos;s meant to be a satire. Alas, it is a great commentary about something - how pretentious - but it is lost in the t</span>
  <span id="freeText6648538585634791183" style="display:none">Ellis is a one-trick pony. This short story collection is simply a regurgitation of <i>Less than Zero</i>. A horrendous effort from an author who proves to be more overrated with each book that I read by him. <i>The Informers</i> contains stories where absolutely nothing happens and the characters are all the same. Ellis confuses apathy; he thinks by writing as such it will deliver this sense. It's meant to be a satire. Alas, it is a great commentary about something - how pretentious - but it is lost in the tedium and horrific repetition. <br /><br />The characters all share the same circle and make appearances in each other's stories, but I could not differentiate one from the other. They are all apathetical bisexual robots who smoke lots of weed, snort cocaine, drink cocktails and eat at fancy restaurants. Everybody is described as being TAN and BLOND. Two words that ended up making me grind my teeth by the time I got to the end of the book. Two words that feature <i>a lot</i> in Ellis's work, particularly in <i>Less than Zero</i>. Of course, it's deliberate, he's making a point about how typical these people are when it comes to their appearance, but it's just lazy writing and tells me that Ellis has no other adjectives in his vocabulary.<br /><br />The writing is poor - lazy and dull - and the dialogue is inane and makes no sense half of the time. There's hardly any clear narrative to the stories, and it just seems to go on and on. Ellis has an irritating habit in this collection of sticking the most outrageous adverbs at the end of dialogue - i.e. <b>'... he says dispassionately.'</b> Jesus f---- wept! <br /><br />I got the impression that Ellis just didn't care. And why should he? He was a fluke to begin with. Here, he was comfortable enough to just string any other nonsense together - actually, I would bet some of these stories were rejected sections from <i>Less than Zero</i> - and sent it off to the publisher, who equally didn't care less because they knew, that by 1994, Ellis was going to sell, regardless of the quality of work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6648538585634791183" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

